<br>
Doofus01 tells you, &quot;Can u sow me plz&quot;<br>
<br>
---<br>
<br>
Then it graduates to:<br>
<br>
Doofus02 tells you, &quot;Can u sow me plz&quot;<br>
<br>
/target doofus02<br>
You see no one by that name.<br>
<br>
/tell Doofus02 I don't see you.<br>
(pause pause pause)<br>
Doofus02 tells you, &quot;Whr r u ill cum 2 u&quot;<br>
<br>
---<br>
<br>
Next in line, same situation, but instead:<br>
<br>
Doofus02 tells you, &quot;I'm at stupidcamp04, which is on the other side of the zone, pls sow me.&quot;<br>
<br>
---<br>
<br>
Well, last night I got a new one.  I was running 3 chars through Skyfire to BWs.  One of the screens on auto-follow got the messages:<br>
<br>
Doofus03 tells you, &quot;wait&quot;<br>
Doofus03 tells you, &quot;can u c2 2 people&quot;<br>
Loading, please wait.<br>
<br>
I saw the messages just before zoning but too late to stop.  I probably wouldn't have backtracked anyway, I was running to help on an epic encounter and wasn't early.<br>
<br>
/tell doofus03 sorry was on auto-follow didn't see your messages until I zoned.<br>
<br>
Doofus03 tells you, &quot;lol&quot;<br>
Doofus03 tells you, &quot;can you zone back and c2 us?&quot;<br>
<br>
/tell doofus03 You've got to be kidding.<br>
<br>
He wasn't kidding.<br>
<br>
I always thought that when I was asking a favor, it was my responsibility to do whatever I could to minimize the impact on the person I was asking.<br>
<br>
In other words, his proper response (if he's going to buff beg in the first place) was:<br>
<br>
Doofus03 tells you, &quot;Are you staying near zone?  I'd like to zone over for c2.&quot;<br>
<br>
---<br>
<br>
Ever notice that the worst buff beggers are the ones who don't play buffing classes?  When a chanter asks me for sow, he ALWAYS offers clarity.  Similarly druids asking for clarity ALWAYS offer sow, and I often see them running around sowing everyone else in sight, too.  Clerics just get jboots and never ask for either, unless it's obviously no imposition at all.<br>
<br>
Wizards used to be bad, then they became better porters than druids.<br>
<br>
---<br>
<br>
This is a pretty lame rant.  It was just one of those head-shaking moments.  &quot;You want me to zone an extra two times to do a favor for you, when it works equally well for you to zone an extra two times to receive said favor?&quot;<br>
<br>
I guess it's like those people who ask for a ride, but don't know where they need to go, aren't ready when they ask, and aren't near either me or a druid ring.<br>
<br>
Get a clue.<br>
